Why Do We Need APIs?

Modern applications are made of many components:

* Mobile Apps
* Web Frontends
* Backend Services
* Databases

These components need a standard way to communicate.

APIs provide that communication layer.

The two most common API architectures today are:

* REST
* GraphQL

Both solve the same problem:

> How can a client request data from a server?

But they solve it in very different ways.

# 🚀 What is REST?

REST (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style introduced by Roy Fielding in 2000.

REST is not a protocol like HTTP.

Instead, it is a set of principles for designing APIs using HTTP.

The central idea behind REST is:

> Everything is treated as a resource.

Examples:

```text
User
Product
Order
Cart
Payment
```

Each resource has its own URL.

Example:

```text
/api/users/123
/api/orders/456
/api/products/789
```

A client interacts with resources using HTTP methods.

# 🔧 REST HTTP Methods

REST primarily uses four HTTP methods.

### GET

Used to retrieve data.

Example:

```http
GET /api/users/123
```

Response:

```json
{
  "id": 123,
  "name": "John",
  "email": "john@email.com"
}
```

### POST

Used to create data.

Example:

```http
POST /api/users
```

Request:

```json
{
  "name": "John",
  "email": "john@email.com"
}
```

### PUT / PATCH

Used to update existing resources.

Example:

```http
PUT /api/users/123
```

### DELETE

Used to remove resources.

Example:

```http
DELETE /api/users/123
```

# 🏗️ How REST Works

Suppose a mobile application needs information about a user.

The client sends:

```http
GET /api/users/123
```

The server:

1. Receives request
2. Queries database
3. Creates JSON response
4. Sends response back

Flow:

```text
Client
   ↓
REST API
   ↓
Database
   ↓
JSON Response
```

# 📊 REST Response Codes

REST APIs use HTTP status codes to indicate result.

### 200 OK

Request successful.

### 201 Created

Resource successfully created.

### 400 Bad Request

Invalid client input.

### 401 Unauthorized

Authentication required.

### 404 Not Found

Resource doesn't exist.

### 500 Internal Server Error

Unexpected server issue.

# ✅ Advantages of REST

### Simple to Understand

URLs naturally map to business entities.

Example:

```text
/users
/orders
/products
```

Developers immediately understand the purpose.

### Stateless

Each request contains all necessary information.

Server doesn't need to remember previous requests.

This makes REST easy to scale horizontally.

### HTTP Caching

REST works naturally with:

* Browser Cache
* CDN Cache
* Reverse Proxies

Example:

```http
GET /api/products
```

can be cached for thousands of users.

### Mature Ecosystem

REST has existed for over two decades.

Almost every language, framework, and cloud provider supports it.

# ❌ Problems with REST

As applications became larger, REST started showing limitations.

# Problem 1: Over-Fetching

Client receives more data than needed.

Example:

Mobile app only needs:

```json
{
  "name": "John",
  "email": "john@email.com"
}
```

But REST returns:

```json
{
  "name": "John",
  "email": "john@email.com",
  "address": "...",
  "phone": "...",
  "createdAt": "...",
  "updatedAt": "..."
}
```

Most of the response is unused.

This wastes bandwidth.

# Problem 2: Under-Fetching

Sometimes REST returns too little information.

Example:

First request:

```http
GET /users/123
```

Second request:

```http
GET /users/123/posts
```

Third request:

```http
GET /users/123/comments
```

The client must make multiple network calls.

This increases latency.

# Problem 3: Versioning

APIs evolve over time.

Old clients still depend on older responses.

This often leads to:

```text
/v1/users
/v2/users
/v3/users
```

Maintaining multiple versions becomes expensive.

# 🚀 What is GraphQL?

GraphQL was developed by Facebook and released in 2015.

Instead of organizing APIs around resources and URLs, GraphQL organizes APIs around data.

The core idea is:

> The client decides exactly what data it wants.

Not the server.

# ⚙️ How GraphQL Works

Unlike REST:

```text
/users
/orders
/products
```

GraphQL usually exposes a single endpoint:

```text
/graphql
```

Client sends a query describing the required data.

Example:

```graphql
query {
  user(id: 123) {
    firstName
    email
    posts {
      title
    }
  }
}
```

GraphQL server gathers data from databases and services and returns exactly what was requested.

Response:

```json
{
  "data": {
    "user": {
      "firstName": "John",
      "email": "john@email.com",
      "posts": [
        {
          "title": "GraphQL Basics"
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

# 🎯 Why GraphQL Was Created

GraphQL was designed to solve REST's biggest weaknesses:

* Over-fetching
* Under-fetching
* API versioning

# Example: REST vs GraphQL

Suppose a page needs:

* User Name
* Email
* Posts

REST:

```http
GET /users/123
GET /users/123/posts
```

Two requests.

GraphQL:

```graphql
query {
  user(id: 123) {
    name
    email
    posts {
      title
    }
  }
}
```

One request.

# 🧩 GraphQL Schema

GraphQL uses strongly typed schemas.

A schema defines:

* Available data
* Relationships
* Data types

Example:

```graphql
type User {
  id: ID!
  name: String!
  email: String!
}
```

This acts as a contract between client and server.

# 🔍 GraphQL Queries

Queries are used to fetch data.

Equivalent to REST GET.

Example:

```graphql
query {
  user(id: 123) {
    name
    email
  }
}
```

# ✏️ GraphQL Mutations

Mutations modify data.

Equivalent to:

* POST
* PUT
* PATCH
* DELETE

Example:

```graphql
mutation {
  createUser(
    name: "John"
    email: "john@email.com"
  ) {
    id
  }
}
```

# 🔄 GraphQL Subscriptions

Subscriptions provide real-time updates.

When data changes, clients receive updates automatically.

Example:

```graphql
subscription {
  newMessage {
    text
    sender
  }
}
```

Useful for:

* Chat Apps
* Notifications
* Live Scores
* Stock Markets

# ✅ Advantages of GraphQL

### Precise Data Fetching

Client receives exactly what it requests.

No over-fetching.

### Single Request

Related data can be fetched together.

No under-fetching.

### Strong Typing

Schema acts as documentation.

Developers know exactly what data exists.

### No API Versioning

New fields can be added without breaking existing queries.

### Built-in Real-Time Support

Subscriptions provide real-time updates.

# ❌ Challenges of GraphQL

### More Complex

Requires:

* Schema
* Resolvers
* GraphQL Server

REST can be built with basic HTTP.

### Harder Caching

REST naturally works with browser and CDN caching.

GraphQL often uses POST requests, making caching harder.

### Risk of Expensive Queries

Clients can request deeply nested data.

Example:

```graphql
User
  → Posts
      → Comments
          → Likes
```

Poorly designed queries can overload databases.

### Security Challenges

Attackers may send extremely large queries.

Depth limiting and query cost analysis are often required.

# ⚔️ REST vs GraphQL

| Feature           | REST           | GraphQL                |
| ----------------- | -------------- | ---------------------- |
| API Style         | Resource Based | Query Based            |
| Endpoints         | Multiple       | Single                 |
| Data Returned     | Server decides | Client decides         |
| Over-Fetching     | Possible       | Avoided                |
| Under-Fetching    | Possible       | Avoided                |
| Caching           | Easy           | Harder                 |
| Complexity        | Simple         | Higher                 |
| Versioning        | Often required | Usually unnecessary    |
| Real-Time Support | Extra setup    | Built-in subscriptions |

# 🏢 When to Use REST

REST is usually better when:

* API is simple
* Data relationships are straightforward
* Heavy caching is needed
* Public APIs are being built

Examples:

* Payment APIs
* Authentication APIs
* CRUD Applications

# 🏢 When to Use GraphQL

GraphQL is usually better when:

* Frontend requirements change frequently
* Multiple clients need different data
* Mobile bandwidth is important
* Data relationships are complex

Examples:

* Social Networks
* Dashboards
* SaaS Platforms
* Mobile Applications


# 🏁 Final Takeaway

REST and GraphQL are two different approaches to API design.

REST organizes APIs around resources and URLs, making it simple, scalable, and easy to cache.

GraphQL organizes APIs around data requirements, giving clients precise control over what they fetch and reducing unnecessary network calls.

Most modern companies use both:

* REST for simple services and public APIs
* GraphQL for complex frontend-driven applications

Understanding the strengths and trade-offs of both is essential for designing scalable and maintainable systems.

